      whence the claim.

Let X be a smooth and proper algebraic variety, and Y a smooth divisor in X. Let j be the inclusion of U=X\setminus Y into X. We have that \mathrm {R}^i j_*\mathbb {Z}=0 for i\neq 0,1, and the Leray spectral sequence for j can be identified with the long exact sequence of cohomology
459hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.1.xmlEquation9.2.1.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1 \ldots \to \operatorname {H}_Y^n(X) \to \operatorname {H}^n(X) \to \operatorname {H}^n(U) \xrightarrow {\partial } \ldots \tag{9.2.1.1}
with \operatorname {H}_Y^n(X) = \operatorname {H}^{n-2}(Y,\operatorname {\mathscr {H}}_Y^2).

For a reason that was made clear in , we identify \operatorname {\mathscr {H}}_Y^2 with the constant sheaf \mathbb {Z}(-1)_\mathbb {Z}. Since the Leray spectral sequence for j converges, by definition, to the mixed Hodge structure of \operatorname {H}^n(U), we find that the exact sequence
460hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.2.xmlEquation9.2.1.2hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1 \ldots \to \operatorname {H}^{n-2}(Y,\mathbb {Z})(-1) \to \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Z}) \to \operatorname {H}^n(U,\mathbb {Z}) \xrightarrow {\partial } \ldots \tag{9.2.1.2}
is an exact sequence of mixed Hodge structures.

The Leray spectral sequence for j is also the spectral sequence of the filtered complex (\Omega _X^\bullet (\log  Y),W);
    the exact sequence above can thus also be identified with that induced by the short exact sequence

    461hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.3hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1.3.xmlEquation9.2.1.3hodge-theory-iii-9.2.1         0         \to  \Omega _X^\bullet          \to  \Omega _X^\bullet (\log  Y)         \xrightarrow {\operatorname {Res}} \Omega _Y^\bullet          \to  0.       \tag{9.2.1.3}       

    For this reason, the homomorphism \partial  in  is also called the residue operator.

The residue operator
463hodge-theory-iii-9.2.2.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.2.1.xmlEquation9.2.2.1hodge-theory-iii-9.2.2 \operatorname {Res}\colon \operatorname {H}^{n+1}(U,\mathbb {Z}) \to \operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Z})(-1) \tag{9.2.2.1}
is strictly compatible with the Hodge filtration. The Hodge filtration of \operatorname {H}^n(U,\mathbb {C}) thus determines that of \operatorname {Ker}(\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {C}))\to \operatorname {H}^{n+2}(X,\mathbb {C}).

We will construct a "compatible system" of affine open covers of the X_n. It will be relevant, for this construction, to consider an open cover of a space Y as a diagram Y \xleftarrow {u} U \xrightarrow {\varphi } I where I is discrete, u is surjective, and u_i\colon U_i\coloneqq \varphi ^{-1}(i)\hookrightarrow Y is an open embedding. Proceeding as in , we construct a diagram
